<article>
    <h1>WHAT THE FRA&#xAD;TER&#xAD;NITY WANTS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200921/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-21"><time>2020-09-21</time></a>
        - <span>SPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>CLEAN UP THEIR ACT</p>
    <p>For the first or­der of the day, I would like to (see them) set­tle the law­suits, start afresh, clean up the house and what­ever in­ef­fi­cien­cies there are in the sec­re­tar­iat. The other thing they can look into is re­viv­ing the sports in­dus­try now that it’s been dev­as­tated, with all the games can­celled. There must be some things for the ath­letes to look for­ward to oth­er­wise they will lose mo­men­tum and drive. Coaches are also anx­ious about how they are go­ing to re­main rel­e­vant in a sport with no com­pe­ti­tion.</p>
    <p>JEZREEL MOK , Wings Ath­letic Club pres­i­dent.</p>
    <p>TWO-WAY AP­PROACH</p>
    <p>It’s all about hav­ing di­a­logues. It can­not be the man­age­ment com­mit­tee com­ing up with poli­cies and not com­mu­ni­cat­ing with ev­ery­one. It should be a con­sul­ta­tive ap­proach. If not, it cre­ates a lot of unnecessar­y ar­gu­ments.</p>
    <p>TAN WEI LEONG , Club Zoom pres­i­dent.</p>
    <p>WIN­NING GOAL</p>
    <p>For an ath­let­ics as­so­ci­a­tion, or any as­so­ci­a­tion for that mat­ter, the top pri­or­ity should be win­ning. They re­ally need to come up with a proper struc­ture and pro­grammes to nur­ture the younger ones or those who are al­ready at the national level and groom them to win medals.</p>
    <p>LAWRENCE LIM , MacRitchie Run­ners 25 pres­i­dent.</p>
    <p>CALIBRATED PLAN</p>
    <p>We are a small pop­u­la­tion and we don’t have a big pool of run­ners so we have to give spe­cial train­ing to them. We have to find a way to give them a proper ed­u­ca­tion, train­ing, nu­tri­tion, th­ese sorts of things. It’s the main task for SA lead­ers to bring them to the in­ter­na­tional level – we don’t want our ath­letes to be one or two laps be­hind. They also have to con­vince par­ents be­cause they are con­cerned with stud­ies in Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>KAN­NAN ARUMUGAM , Sin­ga­pore Masters As­so­ci­a­tion honorary sec­re­tary.</p>


